\subsection{Scalability Analysis}

Scalability is critical for practical visualization. Table \ref{tab:scalability} summarizes how each visualization technique scales with qubit count.

\begin{table}[h!]
	\centering
	\caption{Scalability of Visualization Techniques}
	\label{tab:scalability}
	\begin{tabular}{@{}lcccc@{}}
		\toprule
		\textbf{Visualization} & \textbf{2 qubits} & \textbf{3 qubits} & \textbf{4 qubits} & \textbf{5+ qubits} \\ \midrule
		Bloch Sphere           & Excellent         & Excellent         & Excellent         & Excellent          \\
		State City             & Excellent         & Good              & Challenging       & Impractical        \\
		Cost Landscape         & Excellent         & Excellent         & Excellent         & Excellent          \\
		Circuit Diagram        & Excellent         & Excellent         & Good              & Good               \\
		Dynamic Flow           & Excellent         & Excellent         & Excellent         & Excellent          \\ \bottomrule
	\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\textbf{Key Observation}: State City (density matrix) scales poorly due to exponential growth ($2^n \times 2^n$ matrix), limiting practical use to approximately 4 qubits.

\newpage

\section{Discussion}

\subsection{Hypothesis Validation}

Our results strongly support the hypothesis that certain visualization styles are optimal for specific algorithm families.

\begin{enumerate}
	\item \textbf{Oracle-based algorithms}: Confirmed. Bloch Sphere reveals the geometric rotation mechanism, while State City quantifies probability amplification. Circuit diagrams provide structural context.

	\item \textbf{Transform-based algorithms}: Confirmed. State City is essential because it reveals phase periodicity in the density matrix imaginary part—information that Bloch Sphere cannot capture for multi-qubit systems.

	\item \textbf{Variational algorithms}: Confirmed. Circuit diagrams show ansatz structure and parameter placement, while Cost Landscapes reveal the optimization landscape. Bloch Sphere provides minimal insight.

	\item \textbf{Simulation-based algorithms}: Confirmed. Dynamic Flow and trajectory visualizations are essential for understanding Hamiltonian time evolution.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Visualization Selection Guidelines}

Based on our findings, we provide the following guidelines:

\begin{table}[h!]
	\centering
	\caption{Recommended Visualizations by Algorithm Family}
	\label{tab:guidelines}
	\begin{tabular}{@{}ll@{}}
		\toprule
		\textbf{Algorithm Family} & \textbf{Recommended Visualizations} \\ \midrule
		Oracle-based              & Bloch Sphere + State City + Circuit \\
		Transform-based           & State City + Circuit                \\
		Variational               & Circuit + Cost Landscape            \\
		Simulation-based          & Dynamic Flow + Bloch Trajectory     \\ \bottomrule
	\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\subsection{Trade-offs and Limitations}

\begin{itemize}
	\item \textbf{Bloch Sphere}: Limited to single-qubit states; cannot represent entanglement
	\item \textbf{State City}: Excellent insight but impractical for 5+ qubits
	\item \textbf{Cost Landscape}: Requires parameter sweep computation
	\item \textbf{Dynamic Flow}: Static images; animation would improve understanding
\end{itemize}

\newpage

\section{Conclusions}

This research empirically validated the hypothesis that certain visualization styles are optimal for specific quantum algorithm families. Our key findings are:

\begin{enumerate}
	\item \textbf{Oracle-based algorithms} benefit from the combination of Bloch Sphere (geometric rotation) and State City (probability quantification), with Circuit diagrams providing structural context.

	\item \textbf{Transform-based algorithms} require State City visualization to reveal phase periodicity that cannot be captured by Bloch Sphere for multi-qubit systems.

	\item \textbf{Variational algorithms} need Circuit diagrams (for ansatz structure) and Cost Landscapes (for optimization understanding), as Bloch Sphere provides minimal insight.

	\item \textbf{Simulation-based algorithms} are best understood through Dynamic Flow and trajectory visualizations showing time evolution.

	\item \textbf{Scalability analysis} reveals that State City (density matrix) is practical only for up to 4 qubits, while Bloch Sphere, Circuit diagrams, and Dynamic Flow scale well.
\end{enumerate}

These findings provide practical guidance for researchers and practitioners in selecting appropriate visualization techniques for quantum algorithm analysis.

\subsection{Future Work}

\begin{itemize}
	\item Develop hybrid visualizations combining multiple techniques
	\item Implement interactive/animated visualizations
	\item Extend testing to 10+ qubit systems with alternative density matrix representations
	\item Apply these guidelines to real quantum hardware output visualization
\end{itemize}

